      • HttpResponseContent

        public HttpResponseContent(HttpRequestHeader requestHeader,
                   HttpResponseHeader responseHeader,
                   java.io.BufferedInputStream bIn,
                   int storeMaxReceivedContentSize,
                   int limitMaxReceivedContentSize,
                   int executionStep,
                   java.lang.Object logVectorObject)
                    throws java.io.IOException
        Constructor - reads the HTTP response content.
        Parameters:
        requestHeader - reference to HTTP request header
        responseHeader - reference to HTTP response header
        bIn - buffered input stream from which the response content is read
         
        storeMaxReceivedContentSize - limits storing of the receiving content data up to the given value in bytes (-1 = unlimited, recommended value). Note 1: the content data are fully received, but only a part of them are stored. Note 2: passing another value than -1 may effect that compressed content data cannot be decompressed. Note 3: the size of the stored content data maybe a little bit smaller or larger than the specified maximum value.
         
        limitMaxReceivedContentSize - limits the receiving of content data up to the given value in bytes (-1 = unlimited, recommended value). Note 1: the TCP/IP socket to the web server is maybe closed after receiving data if a limitation is set (HTTP keep-alive disabled for this specific URL call). Note 2: passing another value than -1 maybe affect that compressed content data cannot be decompressed. Note 3: the size of the received content data maybe a little bit larger than the specified maximum value.
         
        executionStep - current execution step of caller (any value is ok)
        logVectorObject - reference to log vector (can be null if no log is needed)
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException

      • getContentLength

        public long getContentLength()
        Returns the real size of the received data - this may include also non-stored data.
        Returns:
        the real size of the received data (number of bytes), or -1 if no content data have been received from the web server.
        See Also:
        storeMaxReceivedContentSizeLimitExceeded()

      • getContent

        public byte[] getContent()
        Returns the received AND also stored content data from the web server as byte[] array, but does not decompress it in case if compressed content data have been received. Hint: you should use in every case the method HttpTestURL.getDecompressedContent().
        Returns:
        the real received AND also stored content data from the web server or null if no content data has been received.
        See Also:
        HttpTestURL.getDecompressedContent(), storeMaxReceivedContentSizeLimitExceeded(), limitMaxReceivedContentSizeLimitExceeded()

      • setContentAfterURLCall

        public void setContentAfterURLCall(byte[] content)
        For internal use only. Overwrite the content of the received data.
        Parameters:
        content - the new content of the (already) received data, or null to clear the content. Note that the HTTP response header field content-length is not updated by this method.
        Since:
        V5.2-V

      • getStoreMaxReceivedContentSize

        public int getStoreMaxReceivedContentSize()
        Returns if storing of the response content data was limited by a maximum size in bytes.
        Returns:
        maximum size in bytes for storing the response content data, or -1 if no limitation was applied.

      • getLimitMaxReceivedContentSize

        public int getLimitMaxReceivedContentSize()
        Returns if receiving of the response content data was limited by a maximum size in bytes.
        Returns:
        maximum size in bytes for receiving the response content data, or -1 if no limitation was applied.

      • storeMaxReceivedContentSizeLimitExceeded

        public boolean storeMaxReceivedContentSizeLimitExceeded()
        Returns if the limit of storing the response content data was exceeded. Note: in the common case that storeMaxReceivedContentSize is set to -1 in the constructor this method returns always false.
        Returns:
        true if the limit of storing the response content data was exceeded, else false.
        See Also:
        getStoreMaxReceivedContentSize()

      • limitMaxReceivedContentSizeLimitExceeded

        public boolean limitMaxReceivedContentSizeLimitExceeded()
        Returns if the limit of reading the response content data from the web server was exceeded. Note: in the common case that limitMaxReceivedContentSize is set to -1 in the constructor this method returns always false.
        Returns:
        true if the limit of reading the response content data from the web server was exceeded, else false.
        See Also:
        getLimitMaxReceivedContentSize()

      • getReceiveTime

        public long getReceiveTime()
        Returns the time between receiving the first byte of the HTTP response content data until the last byte of the HTTP response content data.
        Returns:
        time in milliseconds between receiving the first byte of the HTTP response content data until the last byte of the HTTP response content data, or -1 if no such time was measured.

      • getHttpResponseContentPerformanceData

        Note: such additional data are only collected if the parameter measureResponseContentPerfomanceDetails was set to true in the constructor of this object.
        Returns:
        additional measuring data which have been collected during receiving the content, or null if no additional measuring data are available.
